SIMPLE: song
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Song
<hw>Song</hw> <pr>(s⟦ocr⟧ng; 115)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>song</ets>, <ets>sang</ets>, fr. <ets>singan</ets> to sing; akin to
D. <ets>zang</ets>, G. <ets>sang</ets>, Icel. <ets>s⟦oum⟧ngr</ets>,
Goth. <ets>saggws</ets>. See <er>Sing</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
which is sung or uttered with musical modulations of the voice, whether
of a human being or of a bird, insect, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧That most
ethereal of all sounds, the <xex>song</xex> of crickets.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lyrical poem adapted to vocal music; a
ballad.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>More generally, any poetical strain; a
poem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bard that first adorned our native tongue⟦br⟧
Tuned to his British lyre this ancient <qex>song</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Poetical composition; poetry; verse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This subject for heroic <qex>song</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An object of derision; a laughingstock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now am I their <qex>song</qex>, yea, I am their byword.</q>
<rj><qau>Job xxx. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A trifle; an insignificant sum of money; <as>as, he
bought it for a <ex>song</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The soldier's pay is a
<xex>song</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Silliman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Old song</b></col>, <cd>a trifle; nothing of value.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧I do not intend to be thus put off with an <xex>old
song</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dr. H. More.</au> -- <col><b>Song bird</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any singing bird; one of the
<ord>Oscines</ord>.</cd> -- <col><b>Song sparrow</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very common North American sparrow
(<spn>Melospiza fasciata</spn>, or <spn>Melospiza melodia</spn>) noted
for the sweetness of its song in early spring. Its breast is covered
with dusky brown streaks which form a blotch in the center.</cd> --
<col><b>Song thrush</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a common European
thrush (<spn>Turdus musicus</spn>), noted for its melodius song; --
called also <altname>mavis</altname>, <altname>throstle</altname>, and
<altname>thrasher</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sonnet; ballad; canticle; carol; canzonet; ditty;
hymn; descant; lay; strain; poesy; verse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Songcraft</ent>⟦br⟧
